# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: canoe-sailing-world-championship
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/adirondack-canoe-classic] The **Adirondack Canoe Classic**, also known as the **90-miler**, is a three-day, 90-mile (140 km) canoe race from Old Forge to Saranac Lake in the Adirondacks of New York, United States.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/adirondack-canoe-classic] The race has drawn as many as 500 competitors from California to Florida, New Zealand and Canada paddling 250 canoes, kayaks and guideboats.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/adirondack-canoe-classic] Included in the ninety mile length is 5.25 miles (8.45 km) of carries.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/adirondack-canoe-classic] Held every fall since 1983, the race follows routes traveled by the region’s early settlers and Adirondack guides, a chain of lakes, rivers and carries that is also the first leg of the Northern Forest Canoe Trail.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/adirondack-canoe-classic] The race is limited to 275 boats and fills soon after applications are made available.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/adirondack-canoe-classic] While each year sees a substantial number of true racers, the largest classes are recreational paddlers.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/adirondack-canoe-classic] Many older paddlers participate well into their 70s, and C4 boats with four generations of a family are not unknown.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/adirondack-canoe-classic] There have been many collegiate teams that have competed in the race.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/adirondack-canoe-classic] Hamilton College has a canoe racing team that takes part in the 90-miler every year.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/adirondack-canoe-classic] In 2018, the Hamilton team sent 20 paddlers who all completed the course.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/adirondack-canoe-classic] Classes include C1, C2, C4, K1, K2, War Canoe and Guideboats.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/adirondack-canoe-classic] The route then proceeded via Bartletts Carry to Middle Saranac Lake and Lower Saranac Lake, ending at the New York State Boat Launch on Lake Flower in downtown Saranac Lake.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/adirondack-canoe-classic] Over the years, the route has been adjusted to deal with the logistics of what has become a 250-boat race.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/adirondack-canoe-classic] The route is now broken into three discontinuous one-day segments—the endpoints are chosen with accommodations in mind.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/adirondack-canoe-classic] As a result, the first day's route now proceeds from Old Forge via the Fulton chain, proceeding to the Marion River and the Eckford chain of Lakes to Blue Mountain Lake.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/adirondack-canoe-classic] The second day's race starts near the bottom of Long Lake proceeds via the Raquette River to the New York State boat launch on New York State Route 3, five miles (8 km) east of Tupper Lake.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/adirondack-canoe-classic] The third day starts at the state campground on Fish Creek, off of Upper Saranac Lake and then proceeds via Bartletts Carry to Middle Saranac Lake, the Saranac River, Lower Saranac Lake, Oseetah Lake and Lake Flower, where the race ends at Prescott Park in the village of Saranac Lake.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/adirondack-canoe-classic] There are 5.25 miles (8.45 km) of carries.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/adirondack-canoe-classic] The race is hosted by the New York State Department of Environmental Conservation, the Central Adirondack Association, and the Adirondack Watershed Alliance.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/adirondack-canoe-classic] In 2005 and 2006, the event was named race of the year by the New York Marathon Canoe Racing Association.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships] The **Aerobic Gymnastics World Championships** are the World Championships for aerobic gymnastics.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/albano-buoy-system] The **Albano lane system** is a method of marking kayak, canoe and rowing racecourses using lines of buoys.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/albano-buoy-system] It was first used internationally in the 1960 Summer Olympics held on Lake Albano, Italy.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/albano-buoy-system] It has since become an international standard for most FISA events and is used in Olympic rowing events.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/albano-buoy-system] The marked course is typically straight, and 2000 meters in length.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/albano-buoy-system] The buoy system usually consists of six adjacent 13.5 meter-wide lanes, outlined by 7 lines of small, spherical buoys placed 10 or 15 meters apart.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/albano-buoy-system] The buoys are red for the first and last 100 meters, the rest being white.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/albano-buoy-system] The six lanes are used for racing, and there may also be a separate lane for boats moving from the end of the course to the start line (the up channel).
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/albano-buoy-system] Some courses have as many as eight racing lanes.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/albano-buoy-system] Distances along the course are often marked at intervals, usually every 250 metres, with prominent numbered signs on the shoreline.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/albano-buoy-system] The lane buoys remain in place in most water and weather conditions due to longitudinal wires that are suspended from the buoys at a depth of about 1.5 metres.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/albano-buoy-system] Depending on local conditions, cross-links between the longitudinal wires are attached every 500 metres along the course.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/albano-buoy-system] The system is anchored at intervals and tensioned with weights both in the water and on the shore.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/albano-buoy-system] This allows the entire system to ride up and down with varying water levels.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/albano-buoy-system] In some locations, the entire Albano system can be removed from the racecourse in as little as four hours.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] The **baidarka** or **Aleutian kayak** (Aleut: *iqyax̂*) is a watercraft consisting of soft skin (artificial or natural) over a flexible space frame.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] Without primarily vertical flex, it is not an *iqyax*.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] Its initial design was created by the Aleut people (Unangan/Unangas), the Indigenous people of the Aleutian Islands.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] Aleut are surrounded by treacherous waters and have required water transportation and hunting vessels.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] Due to the geography and climate of the Aleutian Islands, trees and wood were in scarce supply, and the people historically relied primarily on driftwood to create the framework of their kayaks, which they covered in sea mammals skins.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] They developed two types of boats: a hunting kayak with a covered deck, and an open vessel for transportation and capable of carrying goods.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] The word *bidarka* or *baidarka* is the Russian name used for Aleutian style sea kayak.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] The word was coined by early Russian settlers in Alaska, who created it by adding the diminutive suffix "-ka" to the name of another, larger boat that the Aleuts called the umiak and Russians called "baidara".
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] Before the arrival of the Russians, the one-hole baidarkas (kayaks) were found in abundance, along with some two-hole boats.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] The Russians later came to hunt fur-bearing animals, and the Russian influence on the design of the kayaks was significant, resulting in three-hole kayaks.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] These were probably configured with the stern man paddling and guiding the craft, while the bow man was responsible for using the atlatl (throwing board) in the hunt, with the hunt boss in the middle directing the hunt.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] A prominent feature of a baidarka is its forked bow (bifurcated bow).
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] Very lightweight and maneuverable, it was made out of seal skin sewed only by Aleut women, over a frame made strictly of drift wood (since no trees grow in the Aleutian Islands), bone, and sinew.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] It was treated as a living being by Aleut men, and it was taboo for women to handle them once completed.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] The men designed the baidarka frames to be light, fast, and flexible, tying together the wooden parts with intricate and spiritual knots braided from tough animal sinew.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] Unungan women prepared sea lion skins which they sewed onto the frames with bone needles, using a waterproof stitch.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] While out at sea, men carried with them emergency repair kits.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] For the Unungan, the sea kayaks lived as spiritual beings and were essential for their survival.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] From early ages, Unungan boys were trained in the use of baidarka.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] Drawings of the Iqyax - Baidarka are available here.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] In modern times, George Dyson is often credited with the revival of the baidarka, through his company Dyson, Baidarka & Company.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] Dyson and his boats were the subject of Kenneth Brower's book *The Starship and the Canoe*, and Dyson himself wrote the book *Baidarka* in 1986.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] Dyson's Baidarkas are made from modern materials such as aluminium for the frame and coated polyester fabric for the skin.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] Another well known baidarka revivalist is ethnographer David Zimmerly, who has documented the history of baidarka and the people who used them.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] In 1983 Zimmerly published two articles in "Small Boat Journal" that showed how to build a baidarka.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] Modern baidarkas are fast collapsible rowing boats, based on aluminum alloy frame with skin made of PVC fabric.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] Often the inflatable buoyancy chambers are embedded into the skin, resulting in increased safety and performance.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] Some designs additionally support the installation of sail rigging, rudder and fin keel.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aleutian-kayak] Iqyax builders who kept the tradition of building skin-on-skeleton boats alive in the 20th century include Sergie Sovoroff.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/american-canoe-association] The **American Canoe Association** (**ACA**) is the oldest and largest paddle sports organization in the United States, promoting canoeing, kayaking, and rafting.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/american-canoe-association] The ACA sponsors more than seven hundred events each year, along with safety education, instructor certification, waterway conservation and public information campaigns.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/american-canoe-association] There are more than four thousand ACA certified canoe and kayak instructors.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/american-canoe-association] More than two hundred local paddling clubs and fifty thousand individuals are members.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/american-canoe-association] The Association publishes the bi-monthly *Paddler Magazine*.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/american-canoe-association] The ACA was founded in 1880 by Scottish lawyer, John MacGregor, who had founded the British Royal Canoe Club (RCC) in 1866.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/american-canoe-association] In 1883, ACA Secretary Charles Neide and retired sea captain "Barnacle" Kendall paddled and sailed over three thousand miles (4,800 km) from Lake George, New York to Pensacola, Florida.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/american-canoe-association] The site of Neide and Kendall's launch and the formation of the American Canoe Association is located on the grounds of the Wiawaka Holiday House.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/american-canoe-association] In 1886 the ACA and the RCC held the first international canoe sailing regatta.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/american-canoe-association] The Adirondack Museum in Blue Mountain, New York has many artifacts from the early years of the ACA.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] The UIM-ABP **Aquabike World Championship** is a powerboating sports competition.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] The UIM-ABP Aquabike World Championship is the premier class of jetski racing, founded in 1992.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Aquabike jetskis are personal watercraft vehicles purpose-built for racing and modified according to class.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] The UIM-ABP Aquabike World Championship is organized and promoted by H2O Racing Ltd on behalf of the Union Internationale Motonautique (UIM), the governing body of powerboating and the exclusive entity recognized by the International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] This term refers to an Aquabike designed to be stood upon and is powered by rear jet propulsion with a completely closed system.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Skis, by definition, are the most demanding to ride as they require high fitness levels and great physical strength as well as agility in the legs and arms.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] According to the different degrees of modifications to the engine and bodywork, this type of Aquabike is used for three different categories: GP1, GP2 and Stock.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Another category (GP3) also exists in which younger drivers, between the ages of 11 and 14, compete.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Ski bikes are also used in the Freestyle category however this requires further structural changes to the size and motor, allowing the Ski to become considerably shorter in length, lighter in weight and able to perform better at low engine speeds.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Ski bikes are currently used in three different disciplines of the UIM-ABP Aquabike World Championship: Closed Circuit, Parallel Slalom and Freestyle.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Runabout refers to the largest and most powerful bikes in the Championship.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Runabout bikes are designed for driving while seated and feature a saddle (located towards the front) and a rear jet or a completely closed propulsion system.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Runabouts are the most common jetski in the world, as they can also be used for recreational purposes.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] As with Ski bikes, Runabout bikes are used for three different racing categories: GP1, GP2 and Stock, according to the different degrees of modifications to the engine and bodywork.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Runabout bikes are used in five different disciplines of the UIM-ABP Aquabike World Championship: Closed Circuit, Offshore, Endurance, Jet Raid and Parallel Slalom.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Regulations require that the path does not exceed 1300m in length.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] The circuit is marked out by different coloured buoys: yellow (right turn) and red (left turn).
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Riders are required to complete a set number of laps (varies according to racing division) at the end of which, the chequered flag is waved by marshals.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] These races are held across long distances and require serious consideration to be taken for refuelling as this is usually done on land.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] The circuit is bordered by large buoys (visible from long distances) or by natural landmarks like coastline, lighthouses, islands, rocks, etc .
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Endurance races are held on long closed circuits.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] As endurance races are testing the long-term resistance of a rider and their bike, these races tend to last several hours and are more akin to a marathon as opposed to a sprint.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Given the long duration of the race, supplies are required in advance to ensure everything runs smoothly.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Runabout bikes are used in endurance races.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] These races are spread over several stages.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Riders are required to travel long distances marked by checkpoints to complete the race.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] These races are often very time consuming as riders cover one expanse of water, and reach the coast on the other side, where their bike then has to be transported by land to the next race stage.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] This category is more of a competition than a race.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Riders are given a duration of three minutes to perform a rehearsed routine, one at a time.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] The stunts are evaluated by a team of five expert judges.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] The evaluation criteria are: quality, quantity and variety.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] The most common moves are Backflip, Barrel Roll, 360, Superman and Submarine.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Safety and security is of paramount importance during all the races and tests.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Each member of the rescue team present at all races is required to have a certificate proving their ability to rescue and transport personal watercraft and injured riders.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] The support of the firefighters and patrol boats is essential as they ensure the immediate action in case of more serious accidents.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] On the ground, there is a medical team specialised in traumatology who are able to accompany the riders to the closest hospital to the race site.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] In offshore racing, there is also a helicopter rescue service.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/archery-world-cup] The **Archery World Cup** is a competition **outdoor**organized by World Archery, where the archers compete in four stages in four countries and the best eight archers of each category (from 2010, four archers during 2006–09) advance to an additional stage to contest the Archery World Cup Final.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/archery-world-cup] It has received plaudits for its innovative approach to the sport, raising its profile and reach.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/archery-world-cup] From 2013, the World Cup is broadcast live on Eurosport.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/archery-world-cup] It carries sponsorship from Kia and Longines, which supports the annual Longines Prize of Precision for archery, for the "best male and female athletes that master bow and arrow through concentration, balance, accuracy, and skill".
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/archery-world-cup] The following venues have hosted stages of the World Cup Final.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/archery-world-cup] The Longines Prize for Precision is awarded to the male and female archers who shoot the most 10s over the course of the competition at the end of the season.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/archery-world-cup] It has been awarded since 2010 and is awarded to compound and recurve archers in alternate years.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/archery-world-cup] Winners receive a trophy, watch and cash prize of 5,000 CHF.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/archery-world-cup] The following table shows the total number of all medals (including stage and finals).
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/archery-world-cup] The following table shows the total number of individual medals (including stage and finals).
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/archery-world-cup] An **Indoor Archery World Cup** was inaugurated in 2010.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/archery-world-cup] It is played in the off-season (November to February), with fewer stages and the final competed in Las Vegas.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/archery-world-cup] In 2014, the stages were held in Marrakesh, Singapore and Telford.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/archery-world-cup] 2019-2020 Indoor Archery World Series have 6 qualification and one final stage.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/archery-world-cup] After 2018, the World Indoor Archery Championships were discontinued, leaving the Indoor Archery World Series as the premier championship in indoor archery.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/canoe-sailing-world-championship] The **Canoe Sailing World Championships** is an international competition in canoe sailing, sanctioned by the ICF as the premier event in that discipline.
[src:canoe-sailing-world-championship/canoe-sailing-world-championship] The competition was first held in 1961 and has been held roughly every 3 years since.
